abstract: The 25th and 26th of May witnessed another exhibition of Woman's Rights in Ohio. The Convention assembled in the Universalist Church in Ravenna, on the morning of the 25th, the following notorieties being among the parties assembled: Rev. Miss ANTOINETTE BROWN, Mrs. SEVERENCE, Mrs. M. A. BRONSON, CAROLINE STANTON, Mrs. ALDRICH, Ex-Rev. JOE BARKER and L. A. HINE. A few "Bloomers," just enough for variety, were scattered through the audience.

abstract: THE QUICKEST PASSAGE FROM SAN FRANCISCO. --The clipper ship Northern Light, Capt. HATCH, arrived at this port yesterday from San Francisco, in the extraordinary short passage of 76 days. abstract: CASTLE GARDEN.--The NATIONAL GUARD BAND gave their final Concert last evening. The attendance was unusually good; indeed, consider ing the coldness of the weather, we were altogether surprised to see so many crowded benches. The entertainment fully merited the patronage bestowed on it. Instrumental music is destined to become a great feature in our summer amusements, and we could wish that the National Band had arrived at a different determination to its present one.

abstract: More than twenty years have passed since the use of the low pressure engine, in navigating the Mississippi and Ohio, was given up as unprofitable. abstract: The Enchanted Mountain in Texas is an immense oval rock, three hundred feet high, situated about eighty miles north of Bastrop. Its surface is polished, and in sunshine dazzles the beholder at a distance of three or four miles. Those who ascend it have to wear moccasins or stockings, and, like those who went up to Mount Horeb, must put off their shoes. The Camanches perform their religious rites on this singular hill.

abstract: The Bourse, at this moment, is like a blacksmith's bellows--one day it draws a monstrous inhalations, and the next exhausts itself of air, Monday it takes a fall, healthy breath, and Tuesday it has the death rattle in its throat; Wednesday its lungs are again inflated, and Thursday they are like a pricked bladder. abstract: SUN-STROKES.--JACOB HENDRICKSON, a laborer employed on the farm a NATHANIEL NOSTHAND, Sen., Spring field, L. I., on Friday last died from the effects of heat. JOHN SWEELY, a laborer on the farm of WM. VALENTINE, at Flushing, also died last Friday from the effects of heat. Quite a number of persons were prostrated on different farms on the Island on the same day, but we hear of no other cases that terminated fatally.

abstract: HOSPITAL AT CANTON.--A friend has sent us a "brief report of the hospital at Kum-le-fall in Canton, during the year 1852." This institution, we believe, is under the care of the American missionaries at Canton. In 1832, during hospital days, 19,972 persons attended the institution. 6,716 of whom were females; and on Sabbath days, 1,437, of whom 1,862 were females.
